<subSubSection id="2255A743BB9DBD44194872884601F2CD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="taxonomic remarks">
<paragraph id="56EA96490042B44E50B78B30D38980CD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Taxonomic remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2F23CF2EDA4FBA81A9138C0D8A88EBA5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
In our collection, a specimen from Ishigaki-jima Island has the posterior transverse margin of metapectal-propodeal complex that is distinct and extends to spiracle distinctly (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8C5079088FE19136BD66CB1E72D3FBA2" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Pristepyris ishigakiensis, male, A-E, G, H, JI 170808 _ 34, F, TH 190717 _ 42 A head in full-face view B antenna (right) C mandible D mesosoma in lateral view; arrow indicating an angulate corner present on cervical pronotal area E mesosoma in dorsal view; arrows indicating posterior transverse margin extending to spiracle F mesosoma in dorsal view; arrow indicating transverse pronotal carina present G forewing H hindwing. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1102.84953.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/686034" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">6E</figureCitation>
) and the other specimens have the margin that is indistinct as in the original description (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0331B5200C869D5B527EFA6D7530ED9C" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Pristepyris ishigakiensis, male, A-E, G, H, JI 170808 _ 34, F, TH 190717 _ 42 A head in full-face view B antenna (right) C mandible D mesosoma in lateral view; arrow indicating an angulate corner present on cervical pronotal area E mesosoma in dorsal view; arrows indicating posterior transverse margin extending to spiracle F mesosoma in dorsal view; arrow indicating transverse pronotal carina present G forewing H hindwing. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1102.84953.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/686034" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">6F</figureCitation>
). However, there are no remarkable differences between the two forms in male genital morphology and in both the 28S and COI sequences. This fact suggests the conspecificity of the two forms (these are likely geographic variations of a single species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DA853AB20A8C2112341431F208DDCC91" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="88D042AB1A70DDDA9F3158AE0ABCA601" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="97ABE6063A3D4E50099F48EE828C763A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Southern Ryukyus (
<bibRefCitation id="A002F5CE5DE9C4B27789F3B17DD66BE2" author="Terayama, M" journalOrPublisher="Touka Shobo Co, Fukuoka, Japan" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B34" refString="Terayama, M, 2006. The Insects of Japan (Hymenoptera), Vol. 1. Touka Shobo Co, Fukuoka, Japan" title="The Insects of Japan (Hymenoptera), Vol. 1." year="2006">Terayama 2006</bibRefCitation>
), from the north to south of Taiwan (new to Taiwan); evergreen broadleaf forest.
</paragraph>
